<text>DON'T DO IT. TAKE THIS AS A WARNING. Don't, AND I say absolutely don't donate your car to this organization or even at all. I researched and thought this organization isn't like some other organization and I wouldn't have any trouble. I was WRONG. 2 months after I donated my car, I received a ticket through the mail,  I sent in my letter of transfer to the DMV, I contacted the organization. The ticket was resolved. BUT THEN 5 MONTHS LATER (TODAY) I RECEIVED A TOWING LETTER WITH A $700+ FEE, and stating that after 1 months if you don't pay, the towing place have the rights to sell the car.

When you donate your car it's like your car, YOUR BABY is being passed down to different owners who doesn't take care of it OR even bother to register. I have come to realize ALL donated car organization does NOT have a good system to make sure your car is transferred PROPERLY. All they care about is getting it sold and taking that profit. Right now i'm sitting here in the middle of the night and I have to figure this whole situation before this towing place sells my car to ANOTHER owner who may not even register the car. Then what next? this new owner uses my car to commit a crime? and then another letter stating I need to pay for another towing fee. It's NOT worth it. I am writing this because there were so many good reviews. But listen to me, if you can. Sell it for less or to the government. Don't DONATE IT.< /text><Pictures>None<//Pictures><Response>None<//Response>< Name>

< review>
These guys are a class act!! My classic 91 Firebird had been stumbling and stalling from stop signs and red lights for like 4 yrs, had erratic rpms, and smelled strongly of gas . I went in Aamco Cat City already having attitude and on the defensive out of frustration with spending more than i paid for the car 7 years ago at other local shops that fixed everything but what I went to them for, not listening to me, and basically just throwing parts at the car hoping it worked, only to tell me I needed a mechanic that specialized in my late model car. I left my car with Alejandro for his guys to do a preliminary check and when he then said it needed 7 hrs of diagnostics just to find out what was going on I had even more attitude and said "what was that? the pre-diagnostics?". He told me that they wanted to spend the time on it to do it right. At this point I was willing to do anything for my car to stop stalling and risking me getting in an accident, pulled over, or spontaneously combusting!! Something told me to trust him and I am so glad I did! I was prepared for bad news that I needed hundreds of dollars in repairs but Alejandro prioritized my cars issues but only fixed what I brought it there for. He didn't even charge me any more for the actual work done since it was related to a diagnostic I was already paying for, just 2 parts. My car has never run so well and I will be bringing it back to Aamco for all my future car maintenance and repairs! Best of all, no more embarrassment and people behind me beeping when my car dies in the middle of intersections!! Thank you Alejandro. It feels like I got a new car. You and your bomb mechanics are the best!</review>

<rating>5</rating>< text>
You'll never find better people. The moment I walked into their beautiful little shop, I was blown away by how it felt like a place where a community would come together because the owners were so welcoming and helpful.

Daniel and Max are the friendliest, warmest people, always greeting you with a smile and genuine interest in getting to know you. Any time I am there, I just want to stay and hang with them which, thankfully, I can do because they have wine tastings on offer, too.

Most wines are in the $15-25 range, which means you can go back often to bask in the glow of their wonderful hearts while you have a flight or just pick out a bottle for dinner that night.

Don't buy your wine anywhere else. Support these lovely humans by shopping local. Go early, go often!< /text>

<user_id>106835280816149985407</user_id>< name>
Matt Guidi<//name>
< date>
1508282572529<//date>
<Rate>5< /Rate>< text>
I have to say that this is my favorite place to buy wine, or just grab a glass after work (yes, you can drink here too!!). First, the owners, Max and Daniel, are about the nicest people you will ever meet. Plus, they actually know what they are talking about. From the moment they ask if they can help you with anything, you know that they genuinely want to help you find a great wine in your price range, and not just make a sale.

Also, they have a selection of wines that you won't find in most places. The prices range from under $15 a bottle (they have a whole table of them) to upwards of $200 a bottle. I would say most are in the $15 - $30 range.

I just love this place. Also, they just held tastings where all of the proceeds went to support people displaced by the Napa and Sonoma fires. It is a true community spot.< /text>

<Rating>5<//Rating><user_name>Kera Periwinkle<//user_name><Pictures>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNtn1atkr0VmFtsMU61mj0WThWkdb8t8mVljwOv=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]</Pictures><Date>1545041927013< /Date>< Review>
I came here for the $1.00 lamb skewers that my friends were bragging about and they did not disappoint.  Not only were they only $1.00 per skewer, if you ordered ten skewers, then you got one FOR FREE.  WOW.  Like their prices weren't already crazy low, they gotta throw a complimentary one in there too?  Impressive.

The place is tiny, maximum capacity of 13 people, according to the fire department.  Restaurant is clean though and not cluttered at all.  Service is friendly and excellent.  When you walk in, the ladies are there in the corner sliding the raw meat onto the sticks, so you know they're super fresh.

I would totally make the drive for those skewers again.  They were cooked to perfection- slightly fatty, moist and perfectly seasoned with the right amount of cumin.  Loved it!<//Review>

Known as Cua Hui Lou, by those in the know, the sign on its exterior simply says: "Szechuan."

They only take cash, but for really delicious food, it's a minor inconvenience imo.

I've been to a number of Szechuan/Sichuan places and although it's not fancy in terms of ambience and plating of dishes, Cua Hua Lou is my favorite in terms of taste.</Review>

The Thai Steak Sirloin was terrific, tender, and served with a wonderfully flavorful sauce. But the noodles inside the Spring rolls were extra soft, leading to an unexpected squishiness within the otherwise crispy assortment of fresh vegetables. The Salmon Curry was nice, but not spectacular.

< text>
This location scented so a lot like dining establishments in Thailand that it revived a flooding of memories. The fish sauce, the fermented shrimp paste, and also jasmine rice.Service was so on the round as well as they maintained examining on me every couple of minutes waiting on me to buy. Food appeared in a timely style, as well as had a great deal of leftovers so they boxed it up for me.From the Thai cold tea, to the Tom kha gai (coconut chicken soup), to the Bangkok sausages which were so complete of fresh lemongrass, as well as the Khao soi contained taste as well as had the perfect thickness as well as depth of flavor.Was too full for dessert and also loved all the meal, no complaints at all.For sure will certainly be back!< /text>

<Date>1399353240833< /Date><rate>1<//rate>< Review>
I bought a Groupon for this place and have not been able to use it because the restaurant is never open when it says it is.
First, we stopped by on a Sunday at 10:30. Closed but they had menus on the door saying that they where open 11am- 10pm Daily. OK, so we'll wait a bit and come back when they're open, no biggie.
So I dropped off my car down the street to get detailed and we'll eat while we wait for it to get done. We come back at 11:30 and guess what? Still not open. That's weird because their menu clearly says that they should be open and there is no sign to say otherwise. Odd, so I checked the website... it says they're open 11am to 10pm but they're closed on sundays. We'll that sucks, I guess we'll try again for dinner on Monday since they're open late. 9:05pm monday, here we are for the third time and NOPE not open. Not a single light on. Wtf?
Is this place ever open? Maybe I'll never find out...< /Review>

<Date>1368408208068< /Date><rating>5< /rating><review>Delicious!!!! Good location and Excellent service!!!!
I loved the Pad Kee Mow, Pad Khing and Thai Iced tea.<//review><pictures>None</pictures>< Response>

< GmapID>
0x809ad0dae1b2528f:0x7fbbed2dfddd942< /GmapID>
</record></dataset><record>
<Pics>None</Pics>< review>
My wife and I thoroughly enjoy Thai food and have tried MANY Thai restaurants all over the Sacramento area. Swasdee is the best Thai I've ever had in Sacramento.
We had the Crisp Fried Calamary for starters. I've never seen squid served in this way, but it came to us in what can best be described as "calamari chips".  If they sold this stuff in stores, I'd buy it all.  The tangy plum sauce that comes with the calamari for dipping was delicious.
For the main dish, I ordered the Pad Him-ma-parn (the stir fried Cashew plate). The flavors and spices were amazing, the meat was tender and delicious and portions on the lunch plate were perfect.
My wife had Pad Prik Gang (Pumpkin Stir Fried) with tofu. Tasty tofu can be hard to come by if it's not done properly and this was certainly done with care and love.  The flavor penetrated each part of the meal and eventually every part of the pallette.
To finish things up, we ordered the Fried Banana Ice Cream and were presented with a choice of coconut, taro, vanilla, or green tea ice cream (we opted for Coconut).  The dessert came with four adorable (and delicious) banana filled eggrolls which were drizzled with a creamy sweet sauce. the ice cream was delicious and truly wrapped up the whole experience of our meal nicely.
I'd DEFINATELY revisit and will be recommending this establishment to fans of food everywhere. When I complimented the server on a job well done, I discovered that the restaurant is family owned and ran. Our waitress thanked me, saying that they pride themselves on being able to bring the flavors of their much beloved cuisine to the people of Sacramento.  I can't wait to go back!< /review>

< text>
I went in for brake service and they tried to "short stick" me today. They took one look at me and thought I was a young naive female who knows nothing about auto mechanics.

Luckily for me, I grew up on a farm so I know a thing or two about machines not to mention I'm really good with numbers. Cognitive Science happens to be my major.

I know when I'm being played when I'm provided with a laundry list of low-priority repairs if not unnecessary repairs including "a nail in my side wall," that isn't even there after I checked as well as another professional thoroughly checked after leaving there.

They wouldn't answer my clear and concise questions to explain their diagnosis but tried charging me more than $400 for just brake pads alone when I said, "no," to everything else. This cost didn't even include labor.

I tried giving them a chance to re-adjust their estimate, because perhaps the manager who was helping me was just a bit rattled after the man he previously helped loudly complained of problems with their cost breakdown also. Nope. He instead just hit some keys going in and out of the same menus, unclicked and clicked the same check boxes and then showed me the exact same numbers.

When I confronted him, he was silent.

Not only did I look up the cost online to verify my instincts, but I contacted another mechanic (who happens to be my father living in a different state) and went straight to an Autozone. For similar high quality ceramic front and back brake pads, I could get both sets for less than $100. That is more than a $300 markup!

Additionally, how convenient was it that their printer, even though they were printing off sheets with preliminary cost breakdowns for everyone supposedly, "didn't work," when you wanted a physical hard copy of the actual cost breakdown.

Seems to me they don't want evidence that they are indeed ripping people off floating around out in the open.

How can you gentlemen (I'm still trying to be nice) go home, lie to your families about your dishonest commissions and still sleep at night?

You took time away from me that I cannot get back not to mention stressed me out, but do you care? Of course not. Why should you when you can just get away with doing this to others on a daily basis who are unfortunately not as experienced and instinctual as I am. May your bad choices align you with the karma you truly deserve.

I WARN YOU GOOD PEOPLE - as a single female surviving and succeeding in this city - DO NOT GO TO THIS FIRESTONE UNLESS YOU WANT TO BE RIPPED OFF.

Good luck to you all out there in this crazy dishonest world.<//text>

< Review>
I ordered the green tea salad and the veggie soup. I could tell both were quality food. They had great, unique flavor. However, I left never needed to have those dishes again and the problem is me, not them. I realized I just don't love Burmese food, which is odd because it's a combo of Indian, Chinese, and Thai food (all which I love).

They were so kind- the nicest service I had on my entire trip. You feel so special for coming here to eat and they truly are grateful.

It's in the heart of a fun neighborhood, Richmond. When you're done here, walk across the street to Green Apple Books.<//Review>

I got takeout on Saturday afternoon and was surprised at how friendly, helpful, and thoughtful the woman was when I picked up my food. Most places don't add a lot of service or ask any additional questions when you pick up, but that wasn't the case. <Date>1562918575440< /Date><userid>104324583868706101356</userid><text>I never really knew what Burmese food was before but all I know now is that I love it.

Tea Leaf Salad: This salad is a must. Enough said. If you need anymore convincing, many others in the reviews will say the same.

Mango Chicken: Just a little heads up if your spice tolerance is similar to mine (little to none): this was reallllly spicy. I thought I was in the clear because the dish's description didn't have "not available mild" next to it like some others on the menu, but BOY was I wrong. Don't get me wrong, it was still delicious; I just had to take a sip of water after every bite. Thankfully, the service was really good and my water was continuously filled.

Braised Pork Belly with Pickled Mustard Greens: I typically don't like anything "pickled" but this dish changed my mind (at least for now). The thin slices of pork belly were tender and I really enjoyed the sauce it was paired with.<//text><pics>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipPULVfLSybTt8XfMtcPkQBLRAT84z__ry0TZwI=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNyexEQQvix3Adfuz7I__dHOmpVRdrq42DgqqU=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNgcsJBLH19840THPYgyqC6JaNO4_A1IlgVNh8=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]</pics>< Response>

<review>This is one of my favourite restaurants in the city. Super authentic mom-and-pop spot with amazing flavours and quality of food every single time. <date>1604805087387< /date>< Rate>

<Review>For years and years and years I'd heard the tales told around the wonders of Burma Superstar, but mostly due to it's hard to reach location within the City and the likelihood of long lines I'd simply never made the effort. Finally, I was able to give it a shot during the coronavirus quarantine of all times, and it really was magical.

Star 1: How were the service and atmosphere?

Burma Superstar has a great little shop with a quaint atmosphere on a block that's otherwise not entirely noteworthy, and they've adapted to covid nicely with a very refined to-go system. While it was two hours between order and pickup which I knew would be the case ahead of time, I was in and out in five minutes and everything was well packaged. Star.

Star 2: How were the portions relative to the cost?

Burma Superstar is pricey no doubt about it, but so many of these dishes are so unique that you should expect to pay the premium. Even so, ~$15.00 for serving and a half portions of entrees isn't at all unreasonable in San Francisco, and I was able to feed a party of three for about $75. Star.

Stars 3 and 4: How was the food?

Everything, and I mean every single thing that we ordered was out of this world good. The firecracker cauliflower - legendary. The fiery chicken - incredible. Even the coconut rice brought an edge and flavor to an otherwise standard side, and my only regret was that I hadn't ordered more. Two Stars.

Star 5: Would you be excited to go back?

Without question or hesitation. Star.</Review><Pics>None</Pics><Response>None</Response><Gmap_id>0x80857de1843a955f:0x951b79d8c35ce396<//Gmap_id></record>

< text>
We came at 6pm on a Sunday evening, and this place has an hour long wait. It was very good, but I wouldn't wait this long for it again. If you haven't had Burmese food before, it may be more worth it.

Vegetarian samosa soup. This was a surprisingly delicious dish. It tasted a lot like sambar (south Indian dish) with random bits in it. Strong 4/5

Fried catfish curry. This was my favorite dish by far. There are bones so be warned. The fish was good, and with the curry was awesome. I enjoyed the mixture of flavors and textures. 5/5

Chili lamb. This one was very good and very spicy. The meat was juicy and the meat was tangy and spicy. I feel like I've had dishes like this before, and I didn't have to wait an hour for them. 4/5</text>

<rate>5<//rate><Text>Super delicious food, great service, excellent cocktails. A real treat. Highly recommended.

The pumpkin pork stew was amazing. I loved the sesame beef (crunchy and sweet). The tea leaf salad was a little oily, but still very tasty, especially with the dried garbanzo beans. The basil chicken was very satisfying, though not very adventurous. We got some kind of noodles too, which were OK to me, but others in our group loved them. I tried the Temescal and Rangoon Mule cocktails. Both were tasty and refreshing.<//Text>< pictures>

< Text>
Get here early or be prepared to wait! The space inside is already packed to the brim so movement is limited.

Ordered the tea leaf salad, moh hinga, and beef curry.

The beef curry could have been a bit spicier. Probably should have gotten medium instead of mild.

The moh hinga reminded me of bun rieu. The noodles seemed to be the same type of noodles.

The salad was alright. Just seemed like you're eating a salad with fish sauce. Nothing special. I wouldn't order it again.<//Text>

< text>
Wow this place is impressive!
The food is incredible, the staff is friendly, and the prices are very reasonable for such a busy on place. While the wait can be a little intimating we just put our names down and head over to some of the nearby shops and then hit a bar for a quick drink before we got our table.
When people talk about the Inner Richmond Burma Superstar is one of the first places on their minds and I can see why!</text>

< review>
Came in knowing nothing about this restaurant.

My friend and I had just finished a run in Golden Gate Park and we were both starving. He lives next door and highly recommended it so we pulled the trigger. I was not disappointed.

OMGURD!!!!!

They say hunger is the best spice. They were wrong. Whatever Burma Superstar puts in their food is the best spice. Everything from the Platha to the broccoli was out of this world!

You. Cannot. Go. Wrong. Eating. Here.

I plan on coming back.....a lot.

For inquiring minds we ordered:
Platha, broccoli, chicken basil, and the garlic noodles with duck.

All of them were divine.

I also like a to make a shout-out to the ginger lemonade, it was perfectly balanced between sweet and sour. I could drink it all day.</review>

<Rating>4</Rating>< text>
I enjoyed that I got to try something new. I've never had Burmese food and it was definitely interesting. I kept trying to place where the flavors came from or if it was similar to anything else I've eaten. It's definitely a combination of different spices from different countries. I enjoyed most of the food, but would like to try other dishes before I come to a conclusion about how much I like Burmese food. I felt that the dishes I tried could have used just a bit more citrus or fish sauce. But maybe it's because I'm trying to make it seem like another Asian dish.  But if you're looking for something new and different, I'd totally recommend this place and am willing to return. The server made recommendations for my next visit which I think might be more to my liking.</text>

This review is for victuals distributed from Burma Superstar, so doesn't verbalize with the full restaurant experience.  That being verbalized, most of the pabulum peregrinated quite well and made for a very tasty lunch in the FiDi aliment desert.  So jubilant I didn't have to trek to the Avenues and valiant a long wait!

Platha Dipper: Kinda like the Malaysian roti canai, but a much more minuscule quantity of curry to dip in (and no chicken).  The multi-layered fried bread was nice though, albeit a tad cold and not as crispy, likely due to having to peregrinate for distribution.  It was alright, but probably a better in-restaurant snack.

Tea Leaf Salad (Laphet): Their signature dish.  Doesn't look as appealing compared to being accommodated at a restaurant with everything disunited into piles that are commixed table side.  But after some manual effort of pouring on the funky fermented tea leaves and commixing everything yourself, it was fine.  I'm not an immensely colossal salad fan generally, but all the crispy bits paired with the umami fermented teas is just magical.  Peregrinated quite well for distribution.

Garlic Noodles w/ Chicken: Not quite like Vietnamese garlic noodles.  More akin to Chinese lo mein that transpired to have some stewed chicken and an extra dose of garlic.  These were wildly addictive and had a gratifying slurp since they were still partially wet/slick.  I authentically like the stewed chicken in lieu of dry stir-fried chicken.< /Review>

<Time>1514431898295</Time><gmap_id>0x80857de1843a955f:0x951b79d8c35ce396< /gmap_id><pictures>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNh1OpEfsDWRZJp8J_FLr_qclO7mrjPMQnKR2wV=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNHnPf4fLkxgRZkmLWw03LQeU52jQm8pVuAYZm3=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipN_WCw1LndEoFRoLL-yVhFUfWGEZDmjlxdWYGOQ=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]< /pictures><user_name>Madhuja Samaddar</user_name><resp>None< /resp>< Text>
There is probably always a wait here and the place is really packed to the point that you can't get to or from your seat without wobbling neighboring tables with your butt. Even the restroom has a line. But will I come back here? Yes, for sure. I will come here just for the food! The flavors are complex and delectable and the aromas drive you crazy while you wait for your food to arrive. Thankfully once you have ordered, it's not a long wait as the service here is fast as well as courteous and efficient. We ordered the famous tea leaf salad and really enjoyed it especially it's crunchy texture in combination with the soothing tea flavor. We also ordered one of their soups, the Oh Noh Kauswer . It comes as a big broth of tastebud tickling coconutty-lemony-peanutty goodness with generous amounts of noodles, meat and egg. Certainly the heartiest comfort food for a winter day.
I've eaten at other Burmese restaurants too but this one certainly takes the cake.< /Text>

Daly City boasts a Burmese community and authentic Burmese food and a true Burmese atmosphere in its restaurants.  I was at Burma Superstar this evening.  After getting through the temperature check screening and forced hand sanitizer use, we were seated outside (the most extreme COVID measures imposed at any restaurant I've been to). < review>
My friends and I went for brunch on New Year's Day and were lucky enough to be seated immediately (party of 4). Lunchtime may be the solution if you are looking to bypass some of the crowds. We ordered entirely too much food and had ZERO REGRETS as everything was delicious: The Food Network famous tea leaf salad dish, vegetarian soup, platha and dip, basil chicken, Burmese curry, superstar shrimp, vegetarian noodles, and coconut rice. To round out this masterpiece of a meal, the pitcher of mango mimosa was both delightful and well worth your money in alcohol content. Congrats Burma Superstar, you're perfect, you're beautiful, you look like Linda Evangelista, you're a model!< /review>

<user>111986424051194444047<//user>< name>
Freddie Long</name>
<Date>1581936021067<//Date>< rate>
5< /rate>
< Text>
I've been to the Oakland location a few times and was excited to try their SF branch while I was in the area. We went on a weekday night so luckily the wait wasn't too bad. We put our names on the Yelp Waitlist before arriving and it estimated less than a 5 minute wait! Their Tea Leaf Salad is pretty popular but my favorite is their Rainbow Salad. It has 22 different ingredients with four types of noodles and is amazing when mixed together! We also ordered their Burmese Style Curry with Beef with Coconut Rice. The meat was seasoned perfectly and really tender. It's worth it to order the coconut rice since it's only 50 cents more than their regular white/brown rice. It's delicious with their curry!

Parking in this area is a hit/miss depending on day and time. We got lucky and found parking within a half block away on a weekday night.<//Text>

Athena Chang<//username>
<date>1494302554017</date><rate>4<//rate><Text>After hearing so much hype, my husband and I made it to this spot on a late Saturday afternoon for lunch. There was no wait at 2PM and we walked right in. A friendly hostess greeted us right away and we got a corner table.

The menu is quite extensive with all kinds of options including salad, soup, noodles, meat and even desserts. They also have daily lunch special even for the weekends so that is a great deal.

We started with their famous tea leaf salad and lamb samosa as appetizers. We were being quite ambitious because it turns out the salad is huge and comes with unique fermented tea leaf, deep fried peanuts, seeds and some items I cannot recall over a bed of lettuce. The flavor is very unique and tasty. I really enjoyed the texture and flavor and was kind of full already. The lamb samosa reminded me of their Indian counterpart but less curry with an Asian flavor dipping sauce that is sweet and tangy. By this point, I was 75% full.

For entrÃ©e, I opted for their Bun tay Kauser (chicken curry over egg noodles) and my husband ordered the chili lamb special. Both came in again, huge portions. Honestly, my noodle dish was nothing special; it was a mild yellow curry with really tender chicken but the noodles were very soggy. I am not sure if it is normally that soggy or they overcooked it. Nevertheless. the curry tasted fine but nothing special. Chili lamb with rice was very good and it is similar to what we have tasted in some Chinese restaurants but then again, Chinese and Burmese food do share some traits in common.

Overall, it is a great restaurant with unique dishes and somewhat creative menus when it comes to their dessert options and teas. I would love to return to try other dishes.<//Text>< Pictures>

< review>
When I asked friends for San Francisco recommendations, Tartine Bakery and Burma Superstar received the most votes. Here's my experience after a lunch visit on a Tuesday at 1:30pm (I walked right in by the way):

Food: I ordered the green tea salad and the veggie soup. I could tell both were quality food. They had great, unique flavor. However, I left never needed to have those dishes again and the problem is me, not them. I realized I just don't love Burmese food, which is odd because it's a combo of Indian, Chinese, and Thai food (all which I love).

Service: They were so kind- the nicest service I had on my entire trip. You feel so special for coming here to eat and they truly are grateful.

Location: It's in the heart of a fun neighborhood, Richmond. When you're done here, walk across the street to Green Apple Books.</review>

< text>
Burma Superstar came highly recommended by a couple different friends of very different palates, and thus we knew we had to give this place a shot!

The wait goes from nonexistent to extremely long within the first 10 minutes of it opening, so join the waitlist and plan to take a walk.

The tea leaf salad was featured on Food Network and was amazing; please don't miss this. Everything else we ordered was also completely fantastic, and we seriously debated coming back the next day! We even found service to be kind and accommodating as well.

Experience was A+. The most satisfying dinner in SF!</text>

I love this restaurant. I was born in Myanmar aka Burma and grew up eating Burmese food. This restaurant adds a twist to some of the authentic dishes but do it right. For example la phet (tea leaf salad) is served without the lettuce and is a lot more concentrated but at Burma superstar they added lettuce but some how did it right. I loved every thing I tried. So much flavor. Yum!<//Text>

<Review>Burmese is one of my favorite cuisines and I have had at quite a few restaurants in the Bay Area. But Burma Superstar is definitely distinct and better!
1. Sambusa soup - This was a surprise! Distinct taste but very flavorful. Recommended!
2. Rainbow salad - A good mix of soft noodles and crunchy fried onions alongwith fish sauce. Also a bit heavy on the lime. I liked it, but would have preferred if it had something added on the spicy side.
3. Spicy chicken string bean - Good flavor with garlic and pepper feel
4. Vegetarian delux curry - Vegetable medley with dal; the least favorite among what we tried
5. Coconut rice - Plain rice with a slight hint of sweet and coconuty. Recommended!
6. Lychee mojito - Lychee and mint. Definitely recommended!
All in all, a highly recommended place! Be prepared to wait though, the line is always long!<//Review>< user_name>
Rachith Kavi<//user_name>

Excellent service, excellent food, great experience.

We had the famous Tea Leaves Salad, Beef Samusas, Fiery Chicken, Lamb Curry, and both Coconut and Tan Poi rice, split among 3 people it was the right amount.

The stars of the evening were the salad, the samusas and the fiery chicken, they were all flavorful, cooked perfectly. Both rices were also excellent. I was worried the coconut rice would be too sweet but the coconut flavor is  just perfectly applied. The curry was good, not great.

We also had a carafe of the ginger lemonade, which was wonderful. Wish we had tried a noodle dish, will do that next time.

Highly recommended<//text>

Food shouldn't taste this good, but my word BS delivers... The coconut rice has to be laced with crack / cocaine because it's truly addicting. I NEVER reorder a dish at a restaurant in the same sitting, but as a family of 4, we ordered 3 servings of this starchy goodness. Service was smashing and you know a place is doing it right when 3 minutes after they open, there's a wait list. But it's worth the wait. The flavor profile of the dishes was, as others have mentioned, like a party in your mouth. And treat yourself to the Soju spiked with fresh lemon and ginger... it's super refreshing and tasty. Parking is abhorrent, but welcome to San Francisco.< /Review>

<review>Good food. Decent service. Had the skillet sizzling shrimp as starter, absolutely amazing, in 15 years have only found one other place that could do it like this! <review>I ate seriously a lot of great food in the Bay Area, but this place had to be the most surprising and most original. Burmese food is a revelation and Burma Superstar showcases it beautifully. Most "pan-Asian" food presented to an American audience is all the same. As if folks are just taking the same dozen ingredients to make the same dozen dishes. But this food was DIFFERENT as well as being delicious. I was so tempted to get their cookbook, but the food was so complex and elaborately made that I fear that we'd never manage to cook from it. I returned home to hunt down a local Burmese food place and I can only hope they are one tenth as good.</review>< user_id>

< text>
On a day trip to the Bay Area, after a museum, conservatory, and garden visit, my friend and I went to Burma Superstar. She loves the Tea Leaf salad and decided on that and samusa soup combination. I chose the Nan Pia Dok (coconut chicken curry flat flour noodles) and it was probably one of the best dishes I've had in a while. It was brought to the table in a dish with the components separated. The server squeezed lemon on and tossed them together for a perfect bite. While it does include chilies, they were more flavor than heat. Which brings up the service - very friendly and attentive.<//text>

< Review>
You have to get there early for the dinner rush, if not a line starts to form outside the door. This is common for eateries in this part of Berkeley. The restaraunt's description will tell you Burmese food is a reflection of Burma's regional neighbors Thailand, India, and China. It is! Don't be intimidated. All the food is excellent,  but did you really visit it you didn't try the Tea Leaf salad?</Review>

Definitely worth the hype but make sure you add your name to the online wait-list using the Yelp app. That way you can see generally where you are in the line and you can then figure out when to head over to the restaurant so you're not waiting too long outside (there isn't all that much to do in the neighborhood). If you're a fan of Indian you'll love Burmese. Their crispy tofu is my favorite dish.</text>

<Text>Attentive, friendly, and knowledgeable service. The unusual rose tea was from pink roses and had a very mild flavor, and brought a wonderful scent to the table. The menu items that are spicy and cannot be changed in strength are indicated on the menu. The spiciness of many items CAN be changed. Fresh yellow bean tofu was a new experience also, and not like "tofu" most of us know. More of a light paste in cake shapes than a cultured block. Samusa soup was pronounced delicious. Pear sorbet was a little too sweet but came prettily served with diced ripe papaya, young mango, and ripe strawberries. The fresh mint was a good foil for the sweetness.< /Text><Pics>None<//Pics><Resp>None<//Resp>< gmapID>

<UserId.>113369969158814474033<//UserId.><user_name>char mar<//user_name><time>1580574944741</time><Rate>4</Rate>< text>
very unique place with great taste. i really enjoyed the platha and dip, as well as the sesame chicken. the platha is like a burmese version of english yorkshire pudding and the sauce adds a sweet flair. it's really unlike anything i've ever had. the sesame chicken was also really tasty, and it's much better than you'd get from any other place.
while i didn't love them, the rest of my party adored the tea leaf salad and the nan pia dok and say that it's definitely the best food they've had in a while.
the wait staff was super patient, friendly, and helpful, and i appreciated the complimentary tea outside for visitors. i think the prices are a bit out there, but the uniqueness of the food makes up for it.</text>

< Text>
This was the first time I've ever had Burmese food and I'm a huge fan. We came here at 6pm on a Thursday and it was pretty busy. We probably waited around 20m or so. The service was okay, it took awhile for them to come to our table (probably about 10-15 minutes after we had sat down). We opted for the tea leaf salad, garlic noodles with tofu and the mango chicken.

The tea leaf salad came out first, and the server mixed it for us. I was a little confused by the taste, I had read that it was fermented and so it didn't taste at all like I had anticipated. The taste was rather muted, which I preferred to having it have a strong fermented taste. The chicken and the garlic noodles came out quickly after. The garlic noodles were good, but they gave me kind of a pad thai vibe. The mango chicken was delicious, a little spicy but a unique dish.

All in all, I would definitely come back here but I'd order totally different dishes because even though they were good, I bet there even better things on the menu.</Text>

<username>Heliana Mano</username>< Date>
1493423975684<//Date>
< pictures>
[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNCk9CRAE1O0Q_i05s5is8kkJRi7I83C1lBs95s=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipP-qiABfV6MLFa69kq1_wogMlkL5dkyjfXNKNX9=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]< /pictures>
<Review>There is nothing more upsetting than being disappointed from a super hyped rating from a restaurant. Yes, just like anyone else, we had to put our names down and wait for about an hour or less to get a table for 6 which we honestly didn't mind at all since we were prepared for the long wait. We in fact enjoyed having a drink and some snacks at Bitter End which is 1 min from Burma. When our table was ready we were able to be at the restaurant in less than 5 minutes - what a winner!

We get there and the first thing I noticed was how hot the place was - it's a fairly small space and super duper crowded but surprisingly not that loud. Reading all the reviews on yelp, we shared a veg curry which everyone said was nice but i didn't try it, the tea leaf salad which was really fresh and lovely, the garlic chilly prawns which were recommended by the waiter instead of the pumpkin prawns and honestly the prawns were perfectly cooked but there was really an overload of garlic which one could only realise after the meal when all the smells come back to your nose (not so pleasant the aftermath), the chilly beef - i'm a bit puzzled on this one as I think we ordered lamb but it tasted like beef so not sure which one we got but it was really nice and flavourful and lastly we shared the catfish curry. The catfish was the one I was looking forward to and it ended up being super duper fried and dry, so dry you couldn't scoop out the flesh from the skin :( - what a sad meal that was. I've had catfish curry before At Champa Garden in Oakland Laotian style and was superb and in another thai restaurant on grand Ave and it didn't disappoint so i was looking forward to the next satisfying experience from Burma, but I was left sad...I didn't analyse the food and how it tasted then and there because honestly between the 6 of us and the great energy at the restaurant we were having such a nice time and despite the fact that there was still a long line outside no waiter pushed us to leave eventhough we were done with our meal, had paid the bill and was just sitting and chatting away - I thought this was nice of the staff. So  when I was trying everything I really enjoyed all of it but after I went home my tummy started rumbling and had a bit of loosies so least to say i didn't feel well and didn't sleep well through the night and since got few shivers I got panicky that could have been food poisoning - but luckily I was fine so not sure what happened there but definitely was something from the food and perhaps too much of the garlic.

Overall, I'm glad I visited this highly rated place but honestly I was let down. I just can't get over that overly fried catfish :'( and how hot it was inside the restaurant! I'm still gonna give this place the benefit of the doubt and try it out one more time, If i ever have the time to wait that long.< /Review><Rate>3</Rate><gmapID>0x80857de1843a955f:0x951b79d8c35ce396< /gmapID><resp>None< /resp>< user_id>

<user>101745605215871584532< /user>< Name>
William Le</Name>
<Time>1384974204837<//Time>< rating>
4</rating>
< review>
4 and a half stars.

My roommate called in and put our name in and was told the wait would be about an hr. It was actually an hr 30, which isn't too bad. The food is worth the wait in my opinion. Although the place is pretty small overall, it still felt clean and open.

We had the tea leaf salad, spicy lamb, classic shrimp & rice casserole, and pork garlic noodles. Everything was tasty but the MUST HAVES were:

Tea leaf salad - great to start with because it makes you feel like you're eating healthy.... then BAM out comes the mound of rice and deep fried stuff (but at least you had a healthy salad right???). It's actually extremely flavorful and the presentation was very nice as well.

Spicy lamb - I'm all about spicy food so this wasn't very spicy at all but it was very flavorful. The meat was tender and there was a good amount of it.

PS. There's hot tea/heat lamps outside while you wait, which definitely helped. Also go to the ice cream crepe place across the street after for dessert.<//review>

<time>1517259512540<//time><Rate>5<//Rate><text>Burmese food is amazing, flat out, it's a great blend of flavors from Indian, Thai, and Korean, and yet, it's also very easy to do poorly. It falls into a pure comfort food trap pretty easily. This place manages to do Burmese food in a way that is accessible and delicious, familiar and comforting without being plain. Which makes it great if you are taking somebody who hasn't tried Burmese food before, there will be something on the menu they recognize, but it will be different than what they remember. Also, Tea leaf salad is an ready crowd pleaser that will make a person wonder what else they might be missing out on.<//text><Pictures>None</Pictures><Resp>None</Resp>< gmapID>

Cristina Salhuana Bruns< /user_name>
< Review>
Yummy, yummy Burmese food. If you're not familiar, it tastes like a mix between Indian, Chinese, and Thai. Such a great combo!

I always get the Tea Leaf salad - 20 ingredients mixed together to make a light and delicious treat! The flavors of tea leaf and garlic are unlike anything I've tasted! I also recommend the pumpkin curry and the coconut rice but you really can't go wrong!

TIP: get here early, they don't take reservations and will only seat you if your whole party is there!< /Review>

<Review>Battle of the Burmese restaurants: Burma Superstar vs. Mandalay.  For me, Burma wins, mainly because of the vegetarian options.  I do agree with those who say the food can be salty, but I like a lot of salt anyway, so it fits my flavor palate.  I ordered a tofu dish that came with red bell peppers, as well as other veggies.  It looked small, but was surprisingly full about a third in.  And it made great leftovers.

I took my family here recently and they enjoyed it.  The waitress was really attentive and made sure we were taken care of.  She must have great time management because it was a packed house.  We ordered a lot of food ($88 for 7 items to be exact).  The one that stood out was the sesame beef.  It was so tender, and had a great balance of sweet and savory.  I also recommend the platha, which is fried bread.

Go early or be prepared to wait!< /Review>< pics>

< text>
This place is the real deal! It doesn't get any more authentic than Burma Superstar.  I've traveled extensively throughout south east Asia - Thailand, Laos, Cambodia - and know how difficult it is to find authentic south east Asian cuisine.  Don't leave without trying one of the rainbow or tea leave salad (with 22 ingredients!).  Efficient and friendly service, too. When in San Francisco make this restaurant a must see, must eat and must enjoy part of your northern Californian experience!</text>

<userid>106187420653225719450</userid>< name>
NewStar ApplianceRepair<//name>
< Date>
1566307367306< /Date>
<Rating>5<//Rating>< Review>
I was super excited that my first Burmese food experience was in such a well known, highly recommended restaurant. From colleagues with trustworthy palates, to passersby on the street who stopped to comment to their friends alongside them, everyone had positive things to say about this San Francisco establishment.
By the time we were seated, (had to wait at least 20-30 mins but not shabby for such a popular place), we already knew what we were going to order: the famous Tea Leaf and Rainbow Salad, Nan Pia Dok (coconut chicken curry), pumpkin pork stew, and coconut rice along with a tofu dish that was also delicious. I could not decide which salad was my favorite as they had different flavors, but fave dish was definitely the Nan Pia Dok. I loved the variety of textures that you would get in a single dish, let alone in all the dishes. The curries had subtle heat and were not overly creamy or rich.

I think the only thing I would say I could've done without was the black rice pudding for dessert. The rice was a little too al dente for my taste although the combo of fruit with it was refreshing.

The service was also on point-- watching our server mix the salads was like watching a hibachi chef make onion volcanoes. Others came to politely clear our plates and refill our waters frequently, i was very impressed.

I would love love love to take any friends/family visiting San Fran to experience this amazing food anytime!</Review>

<UserId.>102217125735823374958< /UserId.><user_name>Max Heinritz</user_name><date>1393312550389</date>< Rating>
4</Rating>
<Text>Amazing food; great drinks; okay ambiance; okay service; nonexistent and therefore bad reservation system.

Food: the tea leaf salad was crunchy and just a tad savory/oily.  Highly recommended.  The garlic noodles and coconut right were both subtler (read: less flavorful and rich) than I was expecting but were good.  The beef curry's sauce had an amazing flavor but the chunks of meat were quite large and, in the centers, sometimes a little dry.

Ambiance: the t-shirts and awards on the walls are a little tacky.  I liked the wood pillars/paneling and the chandelier in the back.  The main room's lighting was fine but seemed inconsistent with the kind of old Asian vibe the other decor gave off. For some reason I felt like the ceiling should have been lower.

Service: slow to start and curt, but the food came out quickly.

The ginger + beer drink was delicious.

We waited for ~one hour on a Monday night.  I don't think I would wait again.  Apparently you can call to put your name on the list but you don't get assigned a specific time.  I would consider doing that.</Text>< pictures>
None<//pictures>

<Rating>5< /Rating>< Text>
This Burmese restaurant in Inner Richmond came highly recommended by multiple friends. It did not disappoint. I've never had Burmese food before, but the bar has been set high. Their Tea Leaf Salad is mixed right in front of you and has no dressing, yet tastes incredible (the tea comes from Burma). Their coconut rice, is the most delcious rice I've ever eaten. And their mint chicken was spicy and flavorful.</Text>

<user>111356377455489648807< /user><Name>Austin Lau<//Name><date>1430372678173</date>< rating>

< text>
This is my favorite restaurant in San Francisco. It's a go-to spot for out of town guests but always hits the spot for me too. Pro tip: Call ahead to get your name on the list so you don't have to wait an absurd amount of time to get a table in the modestly-sized restaurant. Super friendly people, good for sharing, nice value, great Burmese flavors that masterfully mix between Chinese, Thai, and Indian. My favorites: tea leaf salad, coconut chicken soup, garlic chili shrimp, and chili lamb kebat. Enjoy!<//text>

Well executed, quality food at reasonable prices. We thought the drinks were an especially good deal (all drinks come in individual, shareable and lets-get-hammered serving sizes). Of the handful of dishes we tried, the chili lamb and the tea leaf salad were my favorite. The coconut rice was also really good.

I would definitely recommend ordering a smattering of dishes and sharing between friends - I don't think you can go wrong with any of them here.</text>

<Review>The fine city of San Francisco is a mecca for diverse dining. Burma Superstar needs to be on your list of places to eat.

If you decide to have a bite, be sure to come early for lunch (opens at 11:30AM) and grab a table before the waits could exceed your lunch hour. If you happen to be waiting, they have complimentary tea for your patience.

On to the menu:

Tea Leaf Salad - a MUST! With a list of 10+ fresh ingredients this is the most unique salad I ever had. The server will dress it for you.

Lamb Burmese Style Curry - tender chunks of goat in a rich curry stew. Not too spicy. On the side a scoop of their famous coconut rice.

Nan Gyi Dok (Coconut Chicken Rice Noodles Curry) - similar presentation as the salad. A very mild curry flavor.< /Review>< Resp>
None<//Resp>

<Text>Burma Superstar just lost two loyal customers tonight.  The original 5 star review I wrote a few months ago has changed.

I ordered veggie curry for pickup tonight, and it was more of a bland, watery,  vegetable stew. The seasoning on the vegetables seemed to have washed off because it was so watery. I also ordered veggie samosas and they each had some type of meat in them.

I've visited both the Alameda and San Francisco locations over a span of 5 years for at least 20 times combined. I'm sad to say, their quality of food has declined drastically these last 4 months, as the pickup orders I've placed here have not been 5 star quality.

Tonight was the breaking point for me, I can no longer give them anymore chances. Putting meat in a vegetable dish and serving a watery stew instead of curry,  just shows that their 5 star quality service is no more, and that their chefs don't care about the food like they used to.< /Text>< UserId.>

< review>
Tea leaf salad is an absolute must! (although for its price point, I do think it's a little pricey)

Came here for lunch and had the tea leaf salad and the nan pia dok (flat flour noodles with coconut curry and chicken). I was a little disappointed with the noodles, the flat flour noodles are too thick and there is not enough curry in my opinion. Also, the noodle dish was lukewarm when it was served, and I suspect it's been left standing on the kitchen counter for a while. Lukewarm curries are not exactly my most favorite thing.

However, service was good. I have walked past Burma Superstar a few times in the past and there is always a horrendous line. Showing up at around 2pm on a weekday afternoon definitely worked in my favor. I was seated immediately.

This is one of those places in SF where it's like an institution - you have to come at least once, try it and then decide if you would want to repeat your experience.<//review>

<Review>Every city needs Burmese as much as Thai or Indian, but only SF seems to have realized it. Two tricks for avoiding the wait: Call ahead to get your name on the list, or go for lunch when it's less crowded. Get anything with the coconut chicken curry - especially the noodle soup or platha. The famous rainbow and tea salads are wonderful. Duck noodles, curries, rices, mango chicken, and any eggplant dishes also deserve attention.</Review>< pics>

Great food, very unique style of food compared to everything else around.  The tea leaf salad, samosa soup, and the thick burmese bread (I don't remember the name) - are must haves when you go here.  My brother makes us go every time he's back in town.  Prepare for a long wait especially Th-Sat.  There are no reservations so it's first come... first serve.  That's why the service gets rated good... I'm no fan of no reservation place.  But you can at least wander across the street for a drink while you wait.</review>

< Text>
I had heard about this place from so many people and was so excited to finally make it over for dinner. We read reviews before going and knew to arrive early to avoid a long wait. They have complimentary tea while you wait and, for a party of 2, we only had to wait about ten minutes. The salads on the menu all sounded great and it was really hard to choose from them. We ended up ordering the Rainbow Salad as a starter which has over 22 ingredients and is presented beautifully and mixed table side. We saw salads at many other tables and it seemed like other customers were enjoying them as much as we were. We also ordered a chicken dish which I cannot remember the name of but do recall it had great flavor. Come here for a unique experience but only when you're willing to spend a little more.</Text>

<review>One of my new favorite restaurants in SF!

Tea Leaf Salad - 10/10: What an amazing dish. Must try!

Lettuce Cups - 6/10: Good but nothing special. Slightly on the greasy side.

Vegetarian Samusa Soup - 8/10: very unique soup with an interesting flavor spectrum

Shrimp Curry - 6/10: Standard and basic curry.

<rating>4</rating>< text>
My brother and I had dinner at Burma Superstar two nights ago. I've only been to B Star Bar in the city so I was curious to try Burma Superstar--hoping that the East Bay location would spare us the long wait that is usually to be expected and it did! We only waited for about 20 minutes and were seated promptly.

We shared the tea leaf salad (really tasty, but a little too salty in my opinion), samusa soup (which should go with a side of rice, because I found it salty again), and the garlic noodles with duck. All in all a delicious meal nonetheless. The lychee mint smoothies are super refreshing too!< /text>

<Pics>None<//Pics><userid>105526063606570721427< /userid><Gmap_id>0x80857de1843a955f:0x951b79d8c35ce396</Gmap_id><Text>Gotta love Burmese food! You can't go wrong with this place! I suggest calling ahead of time and getting your name on the list, because this place is pretty packed on weekends. My crew ordered the following dishes:

1. Coconut rice: must have to mix with meats
2. Chili Lamb: one of my favorites, lots of flavor
3. Tea Leaf Salad: I'm a huge fan of TLS, but I have to say the other Burmese place on telegraph (Rangoon Superstar) does this one a bit better. Still really tasty though!
4. Mango Chicken: was pretty good, could of had more flavor
5. Bun Tay Kauser: better than the garlic noodles!! I could have ate this dish forever!

4 of us split these 5 dishes and It came out to about $20 per person, including tips/tax and all that! Well worth it!! I'll be back, for sure!<//Text>< Rate>

< userid>
105422311471309460312</userid>
<Name>Paul Volk<//Name><Time>1393391386415<//Time><rating>4< /rating>< review>
The infamous Burma Superstar. So here's the trick. Come on a weekend at or before 6PM. If you've got a party of 2, you'll get a seat no problem, or at least we did. Here's what we got:

The tealeaf salad (obligatory). Flavorful but not particularly filling. I think I went in with super high expectations on this one; so I'd say it's good but not mind-blowing. Next time I'm getting the rainbow salad.

Garlic Noodles with Duck. I love the Viet style garlic noodles but these are also delicious. I was hoping for more duck though. Not much to be found but what little there was added to the savory flavor.

Burmese Chicken & Shrimp Casserole. I'd rate this side by side with the noodles. Super yummy with chicken, shrimp, biryani rice goodness. Total comfort food.

Overall, it was great. Excited to return and explore the menu (psst...remember, come here on a weekday!)< /review>

<Time>1354901680376<//Time>< text>
Burma Superstar is an amazing culinary experience.  Prior to moving to San Francisco, I had never eaten Burmese food; Burma Superstar serves up an amazing combination of textures and flavors!  If you go, definitely try the Tea Leaf Salad, Nan Pia Dok (my favorite dish), Pea Shoots and Coconut Rice.  Items that may be a good addition, depending on your mood and appetite include the Classic Burmese Chicken Casserole, Samusa Soup (good if it is chilly outside), and Platha & Dip (good extra appetizer).  Enjoy!< /text>

<Review>This is one of the true authentic burma food place in the area. Its a cozy little place and they don't on-call or online reservations, you have to be in person to put down the name. The wait can easily be (atleast) hour+ on weekdays and almost 2 hours on weekends.

You should definitely try their Tea leaf salad and sambusa soup. I am a vegeterian, and can say most of their dishes are really done. Full of exciting flavors with right balance of spiciness.

Highly Recommend, its one of bay area's gem.< /Review>< pics>

<userid>107774945980538414730<//userid><Name>Ram Prashanth<//Name>< Time>

<Rating>5< /Rating><Text>Really good food except for the wait time!< /Text><pics>None<//pics><Resp>None</Resp>< gmapID>
0x80857de1843a955f:0x951b79d8c35ce396</gmapID>

< Pictures>
None</Pictures>
< review>
As if this place needs more good reviews! I first ate here about a year ago, it was a Thursday maybe around 8:30, and me and my dinner date waited about 30 minutes.  The hostess took our phone number, then we walked down the street for a drink at a nearby bar.  The time passed quickly and all of a sudden I was getting a call saying our table was ready!

We ordered the tea leaf salad, samusas, pork curry, and catfish curry.  I have to say, I think the tea leaf salad is overrated.  I thought it was nothing to write home about and I definitely wouldn't waste room in my stomach ordering it again.  Everything else was fantastic though.  The samusas were perfect, crunchy on the outside but pillowy and potatoey on the inside.  The curry that the pork was in was fantastic, I wanted to just eat it with a spoon.  The pork was really tender as well.  The catfish was fried to perfection, the only negative was the bones.  The curry itself was more of a tomato base and while I enjoyed it, the curry on the pork was better.

I can't wait to go back and try more!< /review>

108304371797626810140< /user>
<Name>Tony Quan<//Name>< Date>
1401955307133<//Date>
<rate>5</rate>< review>
One of San Francisco's staple restaurants. The wait here is ridiculous, but the food is definitely delicious and unique. If you're not keen on waiting, there's BStar Bar down the street that serves some Burmese dishes like the Rainbow and Tea Leaf Salads that Burma Superstar has along with other great Asian Fusion dishes.

Pros:
- delicious Burmese dishes: get the tea leaf salad, rainbow salad, samosa soup, curry shrimp, and coconut rice.
- they have delicious cocktails as well, like lychee mojitos and sangrias.

Cons:
- epic wait pretty much any day of the week.< /review>

< userid>
104208059385667896410< /userid>
< name>
Daniel Wang<//name>
<date>1470264117426< /date>< Rate>
5</Rate>
< review>
If you haven't tried Burma Superstar yet, consider it a taste of San Francisco that shouldn't be overlooked.  I strongly considering coming with your friends and family for the first time; this way you can try more dishes. Some dishes are vegan friendly. The waitresses here are extremely helpful with assisting with order suggestions. Food is consistently delicious!

Dishes here are best served family style. The Tea leaf salad is a must try. Tea doesn't always need to be served in a cup. The leaves are fermented and imported direct from Burma. Ask the waiter/waitress to explain the ingredients to you if they don't offer to. Lots of flavor from various spices special to Burma. It's nice to know what you put in your body. :)

San Francisco is typically foggy and cold. The lines can be long but they do offer tea while you wait! A fantastic hot dish to warm you up is the Samusa soup. Not only is it vegetarian, it's probably also from heaven.

Seafood lovers should try the mango shrimp. This dish is well-balanced but loaded with flavor. The shrimp has a great texture, having the chewiness resembling fresh live-caught shrimp.

Just started salivating while writing this. Hope you enjoy Burma Superstar as much as we do. To avoid the long lines, try to get a seat when they first open doors. Be mindful they won't seat you until you entire party is present.

Bon Appetit!

-Daniel<//review>

< user_id>
103043991315027203123< /user_id>
<Name>Yoori Chung<//Name><date>1408611047095</date><Rate>5<//Rate><Review>As soon as we walked in, we must have had a sign on because they asked if we had ever been there before. Burma Superstar also had a few dishes featured on Food Network so I'm sure they get a lot of first-timers.

We ordered the Tea Leaf Salad with a variety of ingredients and flavors explained by the server who came over to mix it up for us as well. We also ordered a side of BOMB coconut rice - you have to try this. I could go back for just this rice.

Our main dishes included the Bun Tay Kauswer which had flour noodles and the server recommended this dish over the one with rice noodles because he said it soaked up the flavor better. He was right and although the description states a "stronger coconut curry sauce," the coconut flavor was not as strong as expected, but still very flavorful.
The Chicken Tofu Kebat was delicious! Everything we ordered was exceptional and the flavors were carefully chosen, you could tell. Although they were not conventional mixes, I thought that's what made them particularly enjoyable. Including dessert with jackfruit and coconut ice cream and fried bananas (ohmygaaaaawd), the bill came out to be a little over 60 including tip.

I can't wait to go back! Really though, I have food dreams.<//Review>< Pics>
None< /Pics>

None<//resp>

<user_id>107697775991359481245<//user_id><name>Tom Boonsiri< /name>< time>
1387136198389</time>
<rating>1</rating>< Text>
DISCLAIMER: I've only been there once and I've noticed that other yelpers say your experience is indicative of what you've ordered so I'm giving this place the benefit of doubt with two stars (it really deserves one star). On the flipside, if you rave about a restaurant shouldn't EVERYTHING on the menu be good?

I've always seen an extremely large crowd gathering outside of this restaurant so I figured I'd check out the hype. I definitely recommend calling an hour ahead through their special wait list hotline (not to be confused with the actual number on the website). Let's not be fooled though, when you are in an asian restaurant and you look around and notice that the entire restaurant is filled with caucasians, you should grab your jacket and make a dash for the door. This truly is the golden rule.

Burmese food is basically repackaged thai food but done wrong. Beef Kebat, nothing short of mediocre or what you could get down the road at Spices II (for half the price). Out of everything I ordered the snap pea shoots was the only thing worth mentioning. Candied ginger flour-less chocolate cake... bleh. Mediocre food is truly not worth an hour wait or writing a complete Yelp review.< /Text>

(Translated by Google) I think this shop is good, especially his chicken fillet is so good, it doesn't eat dry chicken like other Americans at all. I personally like spicy food, so I really like all the dishes here.
It's a bit inconvenient to park here during rush hours. You can't make an appointment and can only wait in line, so it would be better to come later. Two people will be much faster but difficult to order, so four people are a good number.

(Translated by Google) Great restaurant of Burmese food. The flavors are wonderful, the food sharply balanced and its sweetness and every dish is served beautifully. Suitable for everyone, not just for Asian food lovers. The dishes that require mixing / serving - the kind waiters do it for the diner and that in itself is great fun. The service is excellent, the explanations are fluent in English and everything is incredibly sweet. The portions are relatively large (you can order a dish in two sizes and the regular size is large) and the prices are perfectly fair (take into account the tax increment). In short, run here!
